{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17622734","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17622734"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:05:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:05:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16811"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16811","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16811"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.07,0.04,0.07,0.75]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9502"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67251"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9502","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9502"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16811"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52703"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4938"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5221"},{"type":"tags","id":"5223"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22435"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22447"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67251","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67251"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EFentanyl is a commonly used opioid analgesic in both acute and chronic pain management.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the pharmacological properties of fentanyl?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Partial agonist at mu-opioid receptors","Pure antagonist at mu-opioid receptors","Mixed agonist-antagonist at opioid receptors","Selective agonist at kappa-opioid receptors","Full agonist at mu-opioid receptors"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EFentanyl is a \u003Cstrong\u003Efull agonist at mu-opioid receptors\u003C/strong\u003E. Its potency (approximately 100 times greater than morphine) results from strong binding affinity for mu-opioid receptors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPartial agonists at mu-opioid receptors\u003C/strong\u003E like buprenorphine demonstrate a ceiling effect on analgesia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPure antagonists at mu-opioid receptors\u003C/strong\u003E like naloxone competitively block opioid binding rather than activate receptors.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMixed agonist-antagonist at opioid receptors\u003C/strong\u003E describes drugs like nalbuphine that exhibit different activities at different receptor subtypes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFentanyl has some activity at kappa receptors but is far more selective for mu-opioid receptors, so describing it as a \u003Cstrong\u003Eselective agonist at kappa-opioid receptors\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition, fentanyl\u0027s lipophilic properties allow it to rapidly cross the blood-brain barrier, leading to quick onset and brief duration of action. These pharmacokinetic properties make it an ideal choice for procedures requiring rapid pain control.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Fentanyl is a synthetic opioid that acts primarily as a mu-opioid receptor agonist.","Fentanyl is approximately 100 times more potent than morphine.","Fentanyl has a rapid onset and short duration of action due to its high lipid solubility."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.